item.title: National Photographic Portrait Prize 2014
item.description: Wangaratta is delighted to be the only Victorian host venue for The National Photographic Portrait Prize 2014. This is an annual exhibition by the National Portrait Gallery intended to promote the very best in contemporary photographic portraiture by both professional and aspiring Australian photographers. This year's Prize attracted over 1400 entries. Judges Dr Sarah Engledow, National Portrait Gallery Curator, Dr Chris Chapman, National Portrait Gallery Senior Curator and guest judge, acclaimed Australian photographer Greg Weight, selected the final 45 portraits that make up the exhibition.

item.title: Tomás Ford: The Final Chase
item.description:
Award-winning cabaret artist Tomas Ford promises to leave audiences shaken, stirred and thoroughly entertained when he brings his hit Edinburgh Fringe spy thriller The Final Chase to the Butterfly Club.
The Final Chase is a noir-as-hell comedy cabaret featuring the suave Australian spy (Ford) chasing down his arch-nemesis and a devastating femme fatale through Southeast Asia – all set to a pulsing electronic soundtrack and riveting video projections.
As smoothly lethal as Daniel Craig’s James Bond, but with a voice like Hugh Jackman’s, Ford weaves a story of 'raucous, riveting intensity' in a show that received a four-star review in The Scotsman: '...a vivid tale of passion, betrayal and way too much booze that stays with you after the final rifle sight has faded from the screen'.
Ford’s notoriety as an electro-cabaret performer has spread since 2003 through a relentless schedule of touring, performing and recording. His brain-melting live shows see him smashing cabaret into live electronic beats, video projections and myriad costume changes while engaging in a push–pull of love and hate with his audience.

item.title: The Architeam Awards Exhibition
item.description:
The annual Architeam Awards aim to raise the profile of small to medium-sized architecture firms and celebrate their contributions to Victoria’s architectural landscape.
Celebrating a record number of entrants this year, the winners and entrants of the 2014 Architeam Awards will be showcased at a free exhibition.
This year’s award recipients represent a mixture of commercial, residential, sustainable, unbuilt and community projects. Judging the entries this year are Dr. Paul McGillick (independent writer and editor on architecture, art and design), architect Shelley Penn and Professor Des Smith (Deakin University).
For more information on the awards or exhibition please visit the website.

item.title: Pieces and Places
item.description: This is the fourth year where HomeGround has put on an art exhibition and this year it's bigger than ever! With over 75 pieces show casing a wide range of medium. The theme to this year's exhibition is 'Pieces and Place'. What are the pieces and places that remind you of home? Our artists have extended themselves to abstract, portrait and landscape around this theme.

item.title: Night Noodle Markets
item.description:
After a hugely successful opening year in 2013, the Night Noodle Markets are back, bigger than ever and in a new location, transforming Birrarung Marr into an Asian-inspired hawker market, complete with all the colour, flavour and buzzing atmosphere which goes along with it. Almost 300,000 Melburnians and visitors flocked to the markets in 2013 and this year will be even bigger.
This year there are a massive 50 stalls, including Izakaya Den, Longrain, Charlie Dumpling and Mr Miyagi, and a convoy of food trucks dishing up cuisine from every corner of Asia.

item.title: Nicky Barry Stand Up Comedy at Speakeasy HQ
item.description:
After making a massive entrance into the Melbourne comedy scene in 2013, Nicky Barry has gained a cult following of comedy lovers the world over who can relate to her hilarious take on men with no hands, body hair and what it takes to be a woman at the top of a man's world.
Now's your chance to see the hottest comedy newcomer, Nicky Barry, as the headline act, along with Speakeasy HQ's entire 10-act vaudeville show, presenting circus, burlesque, sideshow, comedy, jazz, dance and cabaret.

item.title: Jazz at The Waterfront
item.description:
Only the best at the Waterfront Restaurant. The greatest songs ever written performed by American jazz artist, Connie Lansberg and accompanied by the Norwegian jazz legend Tom Hanssen, with a sprinkling of the best double bass players Melbourne has to offer. All this while you dine on fresh seafood or quality meat dishes and gaze at the water. Come for a drink in the bar or for the whole dining experience.

item.title: Il Giallo Durante il Fascismo
item.description:
The Istituto Italiano di Cultura in association with the Australasian Centre for Italian Studies (ACIS) and La Trobe University presents 'Il "giallo" durante il Fascismo: le serie di Carlo Lucarelli e Maurizio de Giovanni' – a talk in Italian by Dr Barbara Pezzotti, Honorary Research Fellow of ACIS.
Dr Pezzotti will talk about two popular crime series set during the Fascist dictatorship in Italy. The first, by Carlo Lucarelli, features Inspector De Luca who investigates crimes during the Republic of Salo and after World War II, while the second, by Maurizio de Giovanni, showcases Inspector Luigi Alfredo Ricciardi, who uses his 'superpowers' to solve crimes in Naples in the 1930s.
Please note the talk will be in Italian. Light refreshments will be served.
Dr Barbara Pezzotti and Dr Brigid Maher from La Trobe University are organising a one-day symposium dedicated to Italian crime writing entitled 'Why Crime Fiction Matters: The Italian Case', to be held on Friday 21 November at the La Trobe University City Campus, 215 Franklin Street, Melbourne.

item.title: God of Carnage
item.description:
Off the back of their 2014 sellout season of RENT at Chapel off Chapel NEXT STEP PRODUCTIONS presents a high-octane verbal cage match with irrational arguments, and loaded topics of misogyny, racial prejudice and homophobia. The Olivier and Tony Award winning GOD OF CARNAGE plays from 19-29 November at Chapel off Chapel. Before the play begins, two 11 year old children, Benjamin and Henry get involved in an argument. Benjamin knocks out two of Henry’s teeth with a stick. That evening, the parents of both children meet to discuss the matter. Fast-paced and outrageous, GOD OF CARNAGE is a gritty black comedy that has all four parents break down their social niceties to reveal their underlying true colours. NEXT STEP PRODUCTIONS boasts a cast of amazing Australian talent, including: ANNA BURGESS (Australian Tour - 39 Steps, The Producers, The Caretaker Goodbye Miss Monroe) AMANDA McKAY (Short and Sweet 2013 Female Performer of the year, Equus, INXS: Never Tear Us Apart) ALLEN LAVERTY (La Peste, Melbourne Playback Theatre, Shhhh!) BRETT WHITTINGHAM (Standing on Ceremony, Laramie Project, Modern International Debt, Unaustralia)
“GOD OF CANAGE may be a familiar comic journey from A to B, but it travels first class” – NY TIMES

item.title: Expert Night: Spotlight on Female Founders
item.description:
If you're an entrepreneur, a startup founder or an employee thinking of leaving the 9-5 behind – this night is for you.
It's a long road from startup concept to viable business. Those who have succeeded have a lot to share.
Drinks will be provided, with plenty of time to network before and after the panel.

item.title: In Celebration of Photography of The Age Exhibition
item.description:
A collection of some of the famous and memorable photography of The Age, selected from the book of the same name by Kathleen Whelan, In Celebration of Photography of The Age - Newspaper Photography in Australia from glass plate negatives to digital, the exhibition features the work of 31 professional Age photographers, with images of photographs published from 1945 to 2014.
Included are photographs from Joe Armao, Ray Blackbourne, Denis Bull, Hugh Bull, Glenn Campbell, Michael Clayton-Jones, Alex Ellinghausen, Rebecca Hallas, Paul Harris, Ken Irwin, Paul Jeffers, Eddie Jim, John Krutop, John Lamb, Alan Lambert, Ron Lovitt, Wayne Ludbey, Clive Mackinnon, Justin McManus, Andrew Meares, Simon O'Dwyer, Bruce Postle, Michael Rayner, Paul Rovere, Pat Scala, Simon Schluter, Jason South, Danie Sprague, Penny Stephens, Wayne Taylor and Angela Wylie.
Some of the well-known images include St Kilda footballer Nicky Winmar raising his jumper in response to racial taunts (Wayne Ludbey,1993); John Olsen creating a 'light' painting (Joe Armao, 2010); Then Prime Minister, Julia Gillard being escorted away from protestors (Alex Ellinghausen, 2012); The Beatles waving to fans (John Lamb, 1964); Trainer Tommy Woodcock with racing horse Reckless (Bruce Postle, 1977); Gough Whitlam addressing a rally (Michael Rayner 1975) and the Black Saturday bushfires (Jason South, 2009).
The Photography of The Age Exhibition brings to the fore the wonderful imagery and historical importance captured by the Age staff photographers over the years. It is a recognition, celebration and reminder of the extraordinary photographers who contribute daily to Victoria's quality newspaper - The Age.

item.title: Tech Savvy Seniors at Lakes Entrance Library
item.description:
The Lakes Entrance Library will be holding some free technology training Tech Savvy Seniors.
This program has been developed to assist older people who have had limited or no previous experience in using technology to learn new skills for the future.

item.title: Watergardens comes alive this Christmas!
item.description:
Watergardens Town Centre will come alive this Christmas with an amazing array of entertainment and a very special magical Christmas digital interactive clock built in as part of Santa's new forest setting.
The magic of Christmas will kick off on Saturday 15 November at 10.30am, with a spectacular Santa's Arrival which will include a parade throughout the centre, a butterfly enclosure, giveaways, free fairy floss, entertainment and more.
On the stroke of midday, the first ever Christmas show will feature on the 250kg gold clock on the clock's interactive digital face. The wonderful show provides perfect entertainment for shoppers, with a dazzling animatronics show every hour. This unique clock measures two and a half metres and stretches to three point one metres when animated.
In addition to the spectacular clock, Watergardens will bring all the wonder and joy of a traditional Christmas with a myriad of activities. Highlights of the Christmas festival will include dancing elves, aerial ring acts, zorb ball acts, tissu artists, fire shows in Town Square, Chrissie the Christmas fairy and of course the real star of the show Santa.
Watergardens will be buzzing with Christmas excitement this December. Get ready to be thrilled and amazed, with the amazing clock and fun activities that will bring Christmas cheer to young and old!

item.title: RMIT Lightscape Project
item.description:
Material Interruptions, showcases the work of 13 RMIT School of Art students from RMIT's Melbourne and Hong Kong campuses.
Lightbox art installations are installed across three city locations: Rodda Lane; RMIT Building 2 lightwell; and Knox Place at Melbourne Central.
This lightscape project provides an alternative to the traditional gallery and activates areas within the urban landscape.

item.title: Kelly Richardson Exhibition
item.description:
Come to an exhibition of video art by acclaimed Canadian artist Kelly Richardson at Screen Space.
This exhibition forms part of 'Topographic Landscapes', a continuing series of exhibitions at Screen Space that presents video work from the turn-of-the-century which uses computer graphics to augment or construct landscapes.
The exhibition series has included internationally renowned artists Patricia Piccinini and Nicolas Moulin. Kelly Richardson's work is the final presentation in the series and includes two works: Ferman Drive (2003-2005) and howthedevil (2002).

item.title: Feminine Fortitude
item.description:
Feminine Fortitude explores the history of the Abbotsford Convent through the experiences of the many strong and creative women who have called it home.
While photography and fashion are synonymous, Feminine Fortitude takes a different approach to these art forms through the combination of historical and modern photographs with a visual fashion history.
This was achieved through the printing of photos on fabric to be used in the creation of garments, which have then been juxtaposed against fashions from some of the eras of the Abbotsford Convent's history.

item.title: Dank: Spectres of Lignite
item.description:
Dank: Spectres of Lignite is inspired by the strange aesthetic of the photographer's home in the Latrobe Valley, the centre of the brown coal power industry in Victoria. The natural valley landscape is marred by the monumental industrial forms of power stations shrouded in clouds of mist - at once magnificent, menacing and surreal. Since power generation was privatised in the 1990s, the area has existed under a systemic cloud of socio-economic problems, and a pervading sense of unease and anxiety exacerbated by the recent Hazelwood coalmine fire.
Built in 1922, the hulking form of the Yallourn Production Centre administrative building now stands derelict and empty. Simultaneously beautiful and ugly, it exists as the last remnant of an earlier period of optimism and industrialisation. Overshadowed by the monolithic chimneys of the newer power plant nearby, after a short-lived reincarnation as a nightclub (and rumoured brothel), it now stands like an oversized headstone memorialising an era of growth and decay.

item.title: AJCabaret presents Schadenfreude
item.description:
A true post-Weimar 21st-century cabaret starring Alicia Jane Steele, the bastard child of a four-way love affair between Judy Garland, Tom Waits, Bette Milder and Ute Lemper.
With a kick-ass band of crusty old mavericks, AJCabaret combine to form a sublime cocktail of music, narrative, theatre and art that's sophisticated yet bawdy, theatrical and personal, dark and uplifting.

item.title: Absinthe – Misuse, Misunderstanding and Mystery
item.description:
Take an absinthe history tasting tour with matching food from the Ampere kitchen.
Debunk the myths while enjoying the most misunderstood of spirits and discover the real history of absinthe whilst learning the technique of preparation and consumption.
Trace the story from its birth in the small town of Val-de-Travers in Switzerland, through the Belle Epoque golden era of France, the dark days of prohibition and finally its legalisation and resurgence.
Break the myths and misconceptions whilst enjoying the subtle nuances of Absinthe from Switzerland, France and the Czech Republic.
Each absinthe is paired with food from the Ampere kitchen to best highlight the botanicals. Join the enlightened age of absinthe's second coming.

item.title: Abbotsford Convent Pop Up Shop
item.description:
The Abbotsford Convent Pop Up Shop is back with a new year, new look and many beautiful new works up for grabs by our talented creative community!
From handwoven baskets to original prints, wearable art to breathtaking photography and paintings, there will be a plethora of delights to enchant you this Spring/Summer.
With all profits going back to the creators, this fun event connects the Abbotsford Convent creative residents with the wider community.

item.title: Woodman Estate Midweek High Tea
item.description:
Take time out of your week to enjoy High Tea at Woodman Estate!
Seated in the Brasserie overlooking the lake, arrive to white linen table cloths and napery.
Savour the selection of estate made finger sandwiches, hot fresh scones, sweet pastries and cakes on a traditional three tiered stand.
Your service includes unlimited espresso coffee, T2 teas and decadent beverages. The perfect afternoon tea.

item.title: Ronnie Woods Art Exhibition
item.description:
To celebrate the Rolling Stones current Australian tour, Silver K Gallery is delighted to present a beautiful collection of artwork from the famous Rolling Stone - Ronnie Woods.
The show is literally a tour through the life and times of the Rolling Stones, from their early years in England to their explosion onto the world stage.

item.title: Jeremy Blincoe: Chimera of Control
item.description:
When was the last time you went on a bush trek or hiked a mountain just to see the view? Melbourne's answer to Jon Krakauer, artist Jeremy Blincoe, brings you on a journey to see isolated and obscure landscapes juxtaposed with digital elements to seamlessly create a pictorial theatre for the mind to wander.
Jeremy Blincoe will present three works from his highly anticipated new series the Chimera of Control at Fitzroy's Seventh Gallery.

item.title: Merino Month - Free Demonstration and Entertainment
item.description:
November is Merino Month - Free Demonstrations and Entertainment
Looking for something that's free to take the kids to see this coming weekend? Continuing the showcasing of our Natural Fibres: It's "Wool Month" this month.

item.title: The Garden of Forking Paths
item.description:
Sure to strike a chord with gamers from ages 8 to 88, The Garden of Forking Paths revisits examples of very earliest computer games running on the original hardware and brings them together with the latest and most astonoshing technologies.
Offering the opportunity to play an original 1980's computer game (the world's first ever art game) on a historic Commodore 64 or get your hands on a CD-rom! See what the internet used to look like when it first began. Talk to a robot on a vintage TV. See how iPad's are your own personal mini art gallery. Play Virtual Reality to the latest in technology: the cutting edge Oculus Rift headwear.
Running throughout the exhibition, Yarra Ranges Regional Museum is also offering an exciting Summer Program to coincide - Including 'FreePlay Games Showcase' (Wednesday 26th November), in which a number of dynamic designers will demonstrate their latest projects; 'Maker Machine Inventors Workshop' (Saturday 6th December) in which young inventors and tinkerers will have the chance to participate in fun hands-on problem solving activities and see their own robotic creations come to life; 'School Holidays: Fly, weave & follow' (Monday 19th - Wednesday 21st January), in which kids will have the chance to make the most of their remaining school holidays by making their own balloon cars, rockets and creative tapestries as well as taking a special kids' tailor-made tour of the museum'; and 'Secret Sessions' (By appointment, daily), in which you can gain exclusive out-of-hours access to the exhibition and enjoy free reign of the games.

item.title: World Dinners at Man Tong Kitchen
item.description:
Crown Casino's premium authentic Chinese restaurant Man Tong Kitchen, the team behind the highly acclaimed Hutong Dumpling Bars, will be celebrating The Age Good Food Month 2014 with World Dinner events throughout November.
In the evenings, the restaurant will explore the secret tastes of China with a series of World Dinner events featuring an eight-dish banquet menu that gets to the heart of the nation's cuisine.
Running Monday to Thursday evenings in November, the special dining event includes sumptuous items such as hot and sour soup with shredded duck, Man Tong's signature entrée, dongpo pork, sliced wagu beef with enoki mushroom rolls and black pepper sauce, coral trout fillets in sweet sour sauce, fresh fried spicy lobster tail, fried rice with scallops and black truffle and crusted milk custard.

item.title: Tracking with the Pitcha Makin Fellaz Exhibition
item.description:
Come and see the twelve giant animal designs created by kids at ArtPlay with the Pitcha Makin Fellaz. The Fellaz are a group of seven Aboriginal men from Ballarat who create art together and have developed their own unique style. The kids explored aboriginal stories of the Yarra and worked with the Fellaz to learn their techniques. Using stamps, paint and patterns they created two metre high animals.

item.title: North: Excerpts and Essays
item.description:
North excerpts and essays meander the wide-ranging north Queensland landscape from Julie Poulsen's home town of Cairns to the Atherton Tablelands onto Cooktown via the Savannah Way. The interpreted views are mixed elucidations: a broad perspective of the far north Queensland landscape.
These works are often viewed flattened and aerial to allow room for intrinsic local details. Here and there is the cat, the goat, the llama, the horse, the letter box, the mailman, the plumber, the peacock, the chook - all part of the local landscape and its ever revolving story.

item.title: Hexasonic
item.description:
A sonic feast for the senses, Hexasonic brings together artists of the Ableton Live User Group Melbourne and their unique styles for a united sound experiment.
With each act bringing a 20 to 30-minute set of their own audio flavour to the table, styles range from ambient and electro-acoustic to EDM and IDM. There’ll be live looping, real-time FX processing and live remixing of original and improvised electronica.
Step into the Hexadome – Arts Centre Melbourne's new pop-up space – live and undercover on the Theatres Forecourt for two nights only.
Ableton Live User Group Melbourne is a broad community of both professional and amateur music producers who are drawn together with the intention of sharing musical and production ideas.
The group welcomes all attendees, no matter what level of experience they have with Ableton Live, and offers a chance to meet with other producers, share knowledge, get feedback and hang out with other like-minded enthusiasts.
Free sessions are held each month at Arts Centre Melbourne, in which both guest speakers and group members are encouraged to get up and show their latest work, production techniques and live sets.
Source: City of Melbourne What's On

item.title: Divine Agencies
item.description:
Throughout the ages, different religions have had visions of messengers of the gods. This exhibition explores the different concepts called angels, seraphim and cherubim, and the various mythologies surrounding angelic winged creatures.
The paintings explore different mythological representations of angels from several cultures, past and present.
Source: City of Melbourne What's On

item.description:

item.title: Slipping Away: New works by Dorota Connellan
item.description:
Slipping Away will invite audiences to take a journey of reflection, to imagine and believe, to be inspired, to seek, to discover and choose.
Dorota Connellan invites you to look around and feel that you are part of one fabulous organism and accept your place among all organisms and to responsibly build a new relationship with Mother Earth.
Dorota's oil paintings are surreal; they are a deployment of imagination where the landscape and figures blend harmoniously in colourful compositions and atmospheres. Her works seem to float in an unknown time and space, in a world of dream and imagination.

item.title: Evoke II - Celine Donegan Exhibition
item.description:
Evoke II is a Celine Donegan exhibition that will be held in The Convent Gallery in Daylesford.
Celine Donegan is an expressionist style painter, working in oils. Her paintings have been exhibited in Australian galleries since 2002 and are in collections in Australia, England, France, Germany, Croatia and Sweden. Her studio base, Luck St Studio is situated in the small Adelaide Hills town of Macclesfield (established 2005).
In 2011 Celine was nominated for the prestigious International Palm Art Award in Leipzig, Germany and again in 2013 for the tenth Anniversary of the Palm Art Award (for which she was awarded a certificate of excellence).
An invitation to exhibit with Trevisan International Arts/TIA, Italy commenced with participation in small works exhibition in Bologna in 2013.

item.title: The Age Good Food Month
item.description:
As if November in Melbourne couldn't get any better, The Age Good Food Month presented by Citi bolts out of the gates with a bumper program of culinary delights celebrating Victoria's world-class food and drinking scene.
In its second year, Good Food Month returns with a line-up of culinary greats, including chef, restaurateur, author and all-round global sensation Yotam Ottolenghi; Italy's biggest skinny Italian chef and contemporary art doyen Massimo Bottura; and arguably one of the most important food thinkers of this time and the woman who put a kitchen garden in The White House, Alice Waters, making her first ever trip to Australia.
Alongside this stellar field of imports are local stars such as The Age Good Food Guide Chef of the Year Andrew McConnell, Melbourne's favourite son Shannon Bennett of Vue de Monde, and rising challengers like Dave Verheul of The Town Mouse - all part of the action-packed program of more than 350 events.
Melburnians can expect an opening weekend full of fire and flavour, smoke and sizzle with Saturday's day of Barbecue Madness. Take your pick from beers and rare-breed meats by the river at The General Assembly at South Wharf, Meatmother's hot chicken challenge, Thai Beach BBQ at Red Spice Road and the food truck barbecue cook-off at the Testing Grounds in Southbank.
Good Food Month has every meal of the day covered with Breakfast Club, Let's Do Lunch, Hats Off Dinners, Good Dinners Under $30 and Let's Do Dessert menus all on offer.

item.title: Element
item.description:
Element is a Latrobe Regional Gallery and Gippsland Art Gallery Collection Exhibition.
Stephen Wickham's large brooding photographs of snow covered rocks stimulated the search for works from the Latrobe Regional Gallery and Gippsland Art Gallery collections that freeze, sparkle, burn, melt and embed themselves in the landscape. The works selected create new associations with raw, tangible materials and consider how far physical elements form a strong part of creating meaning.

item.title: The Classics
item.description:
Funny, playful, and like good wine, vintage is better! Living legends of Australian Circus strut their stuff, proving the golden years are just the beginning of new adventures!
Laugh? Your teeth'll fall out.
Deb Batton and Sue Broadway, along with fellow Cinquegenarians and special guests, will charm you with their wit, fearless presence, and some good old classic Circus tricks!
Performers will be Deb Batton & Sue Broadway, Tim Coldwell, Anni Davey, Kathryn Niesche, Teresa Blake, Robin Laurie & Jon Hawkes, Eleanor Tan, Steven Richards and special guests.

item.title: 'Till Death by Julia deVille
item.description:
'Till Death is an exhibition of new precious stone rings by acclaimed artist and taxidermist Julia deVille, presented by e.g.etal, contemporary jewellery and objects.
This new body of work comprises intricately handcrafted large cluster dress rings in silver and gold - often an amalgamation of new gems set alongside old-cut stones reclaimed from antique rings. Each ring has the appearance of a collection of family heirlooms that have been melded gracefully into one piece.
The exhibition's name, 'Till Death, reflects not only the pieces' intended use as engagement rings and tokens of affection, but also evokes deVille's fascination with the acceptance of death. Julia deVille is inspired by the memento mori jewellery of the 15th to 18th centuries, as well as the methods the Victorians used to sentimentalise death with adornment. The artist incorporates symbols of death throughout her work - a celebration of life through an acknowledgement of your own mortality.

item.title: Tales of a City by the Sea
item.description:
Tales of a City by the Sea is a unique and poetic journey into the lives of ordinary people in the besieged Gaza strip prior to, during and after its bombardment during the winter of 2008.
Jomana, a Palestinian woman who lives in the Shati (beach) refugee camp in Gaza falls in love with Rami, an American-born Palestinian doctor and activist who arrives on the first Free Gaza boats in 2008. Their love is met with many challenges forcing Rami to make incredible decisions, the least of which is to take a dangerous journey through the underground tunnels that connect Gaza to Egypt.
Although this love story appears to explore the relationship between diaspora Palestinians and Palestinians under occupation, there are broader and more universal themes that emerge - of human survival and tenacity.
Although the play's characters are fictional, the script is based on real-life events. The author, Samah Sabawi, wrote most of the poetry in the play during the three-week bombardment of Gaza in 2008-2009.
Written by Samah Sabawi, directed by Lech Mackiewicz.

item.title: New World Dreaming
item.description:
Melbourne is built on the footprints of immigrants, most of whom came through the port and docklands.
In the 1850s Andrew's Irish great-great-grandparents fled the blighted potato fields of Donegal and reached Melbourne, via India in rebellion. They arrived in Melbourne in summer, to a welcome of bushfires, wild dogs and news of the Great Melbourne Telescope gazing at the heavens.
Peter's in-laws left Calabria in the 1950s, where the war had destroyed the established order in their village. Women did men's work and men, especially the ones who had been prisoners of war, had glimpsed other ways of life. When the old order began to reassert itself those who expected more of life had to look elsewhere. Peter's in-laws headed for Melbourne.
Andrew and Peter are seasoned storytellers and in this intimate production they use music and spoken word to give expression to the lives of a few of the millions fleeing the stagnation and turmoil of old worlds to make a life for themselves in a new one.

item.title: National Novel Writing Month: Writing Sessions for Teens
item.description:
Teens, are you tackling the National Novel Writing Month challenge this November?
On Mondays and Wednesdays in November, National Novel Writing Month, drop by to connect with other teen writers and spur on your word count with mid-week sessions.
On Saturdays in November, get hands-on and troubleshoot your work-in-progress at a weekend session hosted by a Young Adult author.

item.title: Barriers to Education
item.description:
Explore an interactive installation that uncovers the world's greatest challenges to education, in the Swanston St Forecourt of Federation Square.
Barriers to Education is a school-based initiative of Save the Children Australia. The program focuses on education as a fundamental right of all children and highlights the key barriers to learning for children around the world.

item.title: Australian Cricketers' Association Event
item.description:
The Australian Cricketers' Association (ACA) Masters are coming to Sun Country on the Murray
The ACA Masters Sportsman's Night will be held on Saturday 29th November at the Yarrawonga Mulwala Cricket Club.
See the legends of the game play at Stan Hargreaves Oval on Sunday 30th November 2014.

item.title: Receivers
item.description:
An absurd, dark, sci-fi comedy, Receivers explores the world of idealistic farmer Hedrick who, after years at agricultural school, simply cannot make things grow. In a final attempt to save his property from ruin he stumbles into a world populated with a prostitute, a General, a television repair man, an unforgiving computer... and Hillary.
Or does he?
Welcome to Latin 4 space platform.
Writer Gareth Ellis was the recipient of the Wal Cherry Award and Malcolm Robertson Prize for his first full length play A View of Concrete. He has written numerous other works including Time With Mrs. Thompson, The Champion Male, I Am A Pessimist, The WeWak Mosquito, The Piano Thief, A Protest and, most recently, The Sound Of Waves. A VCA graduate, Gareth has worked with some of Melbourne's most widely recognised companies including the Melbourne Theatre Company, Illbijerri, Melbourne Workers Theatre, and Arena Theatre Company.
Running since 2010, Feat Theatre is a privately run space, owned and operated by directors of Feat In Space Theatre Company, Amanda Falson and Gareth Ellis. The company is widely recognised as consistently creating and supporting new Australian work, and invite you to join them as they officially launch their new venue with this premiere season.

item.title: Good Food Ballarat
item.description:
This November, The Courier presents Good Food Ballarat, a month long celebration of the local venues, menus and producers that have changed the landscape of Ballarat's food culture.
Throughout November, restaurants and cafes will be hosting a range of special events, featuring local produce with a twist.
Join the dumpling discovery at Fu Man Lou, try a Thai street food lunch at Catfish, a Spanish social night at Café Meigas or experience the region at Jackson's and Co to name a few. There's also Ballarat By The Glass, a series of open cellar doors, wine matched dinners and wine and music weekends held right here in Ballarat.
On Friday, November 28, The Mining Exchange in Lydiard Street will play host to The Family Hawkers Market. This will provide a unique opportunity to come along with the kids, grandparents, or a group of friends and purchase delicious tasting-size portions from a great selection of Ballarat venues you may not have had a chance to visit throughout the month. On offer will be Japanese samplers, sliders, tacos, ribs, dumplings, wood fired pizzas and sausages, plus dessert pastries and Sovereign Hill's famous boiled lollies, all accompanied by locally made wine, beer, cocktails, coffee and drinking chocolates.
The ultimate foodie finale of Good Food Ballarat is a Taste of Ballarat Degustation Dinner on November 29, also at The Mining Exchange. Working with special guest chef Stefano de Pieri, some of Ballarat's top chefs will produce a spectacular five course feast matched with local wines and boutique local beers.
Good Food Ballarat offers something for everyone. Allow yourself to indulge in the best of Ballarat's food and wine offerings this November.

item.title: Marise Maas – Trying Not To Worry
item.description:
Examining Marise Maas' paintings is like peering into a series of little precarious worlds - each bearing the trace of some implicit, destabilising truth. Here, roof tiles are formed from haphazard lines; windows float up and away from their foundational structures; houses teeter on disjointed stilts; electricity pylons and cranes tilt ever so slightly. On a domestic scale, small inert objects such as bowls, take-away containers or coffee cups, stack and tumble off flat slopes of colour, losing any gravitational connection to their once intended utility.
This selection of seemingly mundane motifs in her exhibition Trying Not to Worry holds very real significance for Maas. Informed by what she describes as the bubble of her own local surroundings and domestic family life, the act of painting serves as a kind of diaristic process through which the comprehension, or perhaps apprehension, of daily life takes place.
Items from the kitchen table, backyard or local sports oval all become potential vehicles for the expression of the private logic of her thoughts and fragmentary connections. Honest feelings of anxiety, consternation or whim are allowed to distort the concrete actuality of her subjects, giving rise to a potentially cryptic collection of amusing, somewhat ambiguous narratives.

item.title: Dreamers
item.description:
See the Australian premiere production of the play Dreamers, written by Daniel Keene and directed by Ariette Taylor.
Dreamers deals with questions at the heart of contemporary life – the struggle against intolerance, the fear of difference and a love that is perceived as inappropriate.
Dreamers explores a young man's experience trying to establish himself in a new country, amid growing fear and animosity as he begins a relationship with an older woman, who is also familiar with isolation and loneliness.
The team at fortyfivedownstairs are thrilled to bring together this extraordinary creative team for the first time in over a decade. They previously collaborated in the highly successful and ground-breaking Keene Taylor Theatre Project which ran from 1997 until 2002.
Dreamers will build upon this extraordinary collaboration, whilst producing a play with searing contemporary relevance. The cast includes Helen Morse, Paul English, Nicholas Bell, Marco Chiappi and Natasha Herbert.
Source: City of Melbourne What's On

item.title: Rohan Wealleans: In Space No One Can Hear You Collect Rocks
item.description:
New Zealand artist Rohan Wealleans creates paintings and sculptures comprised of multitudinous layers of house paint that are then incised to reveal the multi-coloured excavations beneath.
The resulting paint chips generated by this process often become art objects in their own right. For Mailbox, they are presented as specimen-like curiosities, and as body adornments in photographs featuring Wealleans-styled naked alien babes. Part 'geologist', part voyeur, Wealleans always inhabits multiple guises.
Curated by Serena Bentley.
Rohan Wealleans is represented by Ivan Anthony Gallery, Auckland; Hamish McKay Gallery, Wellington and Roslyn Oxley9 Gallery, Sydney.

item.title: Australia Will Be There: Victorians In the First World War (1914 – 1919)
item.description:
Australia Will Be There, honouring the centenary of the First World War, will present, through historical photographs and personal stories, a chronology of the war with particular reference to the contribution of Victorians.
Most Australian families lost loved ones, and all made sacrifices, as their sons, fathers, husbands, brothers, uncles and daughters left to serve at the frontline. At home, they waited for news of loved ones and endured their losses, weathered extreme political upheaval, shortages of essentials and worked tirelessly to provide voluntary assistance for those who served.
On 23 October 2014 Australia Will Be There will commence a four year tour of Victoria at the East Gippsland Art Gallery, Bairnsdale. It will tour some twenty venues throughout regional Victoria over the next four years.

item.title: Grommets, grinds and gnarly dudes
item.description:
The Gallery at Bayside Arts & Cultural Centre proudly presents Grommets, grinds and gnarly dudes.
In this exhibition, contemporary artists Phillip George, Gerry Wedd and Jud Wimhurst have used various media to highlight aspects of the history and development of (and connection between) surfing and skating.
Each artist has drawn on the rich narratives and visual imagery inherent within these realms to produce contemporary work that critically interrogates our relationship to these sports, and questions the notion of a singular national identity.
Alongside in Gallery One will be the skateboard and ephemera collection from former state champion skate boarder turned skate park designer, Tony Hallam.

item.title: Ding Dong Lounge presents
item.description:
Nestled in the heart of Chinatown, Ding Dong Lounge, one of Melbourne's most iconic alternative music venues, present a stellar line-up for Live Music Safari.
A strong east coast trifecta, the event features Sydney folk/soul artist Ngaiire, Melbourne's very own Jakubi and a special guest opener from Brisbane.
Sydney singer/songwriter Ngaiire is building a name for herself as one of the country's most dynamic vocalists and performers. Captivating audiences with her soulful voice and powerful music, Ngaiire is changing the face of Australian folk/soul music. With an Australian Music Prize nomination, a spot at Soulfest, a string of UK shows and a Glastonbury performance under her belt, 2014 is shaping up to be a big year for the artist.
After releasing their first three singles online, in little over four months Melbourne's Jakubi reached one million plays via YouTube and SoundCloud. After this astounding achievement, the hip-hop/pop collective have sold out venues across Australia (including at Ding Dong Lounge) and are set to work on a collaboration with Mike Posner, who is responsible for writing songs for Justin Bieber, Pharrell Williams, Nelly and Snoop Dogg, in the States.

item.title: The Mercat presents
item.description:
A brood of local beat makers and DJs create a bounty of electronic, sonic wonderment deep in the sweaty dance haven that is The Mercat basement.
Recently named one of Melbourne's 'best kept secrets' by Tone Deaf, four piece Rat & Co open hearts with alluring beats born from wide-eyed looks at hard and industrial city environments. On the back of the release of their second album Binary and second single 'Samurai', an ode to Japanese hip-hop producer Nujabes, Rat & Co play live with exceptional company.
Expect enigmatic sets from the crew behind Animals Dancing with resident DJs Otologic, Tornado Wallace and Andee Frost taking turns. Cult figures of Melbourne's underground, well-versed in throwing parties in the depths of The Mercat basement, this collective drop everything from acid house to disco and mash a multitude of trans-atlantic sounds.
Get lost in the haze of smoke machines and take home a limited edition 7 inch, pressed especially, featuring tracks from the night's acts.

item.title: The John Curtin Hotel presents
item.description:
The John Curtin Hotel presents a night of disco discovery through the windows of time.
Opening in shimmering spectacle, the Sugar Fed Leopards are three female singers, accompanied by spangling guitars and a solid rhythm section, who are sure to conjure Ike-and-Tina magic with their soul-twisted disco originals.
Next up is a nine-piece explosion of yacht-rock, RnB and synth-funk. Cult favourites Sex On Toast break out vocal harmonies, talk-box synthesizers, drum machines and choreographed dance moves.
Finally, Vaudeville Smash catapult the night into disco bliss by sweeping crowds into a 1980s montage that inspires conga lines for roller limbo and the application of copious amounts of glitter.

item.title: The Public Bar presents
item.description:
Back for more in 2014, The Public Bar, North Melbourne's finest dive bar, throws its doors open for another aural expedition of Melbourne acts for Live Music Safari.
Gold Nights, produced by Alex Akers of Forces and released on It Records, has been recognised internationally. White Hex is all 1980s synth, surf guitar and doom vocals set against the cold backlash of a drum machine. The stellar line-up also features local trio Pearls with their sweet melodies, wandering fuzzy guitar lines and hypnotic drums.
Fellow It (Records) kids Little Desert make music with a 1980s post-punk sensibility. Their duelling female vocals and guitar deliver the night's melancholic finale.
Live recordings of the night's performances will be made available free for download.

item.title: 20,000 Days on Earth
item.description:
Before they officially open for the season, Melbourne's favourite summertime cinema warm up the surround sound system with a three-day series of music films especially programmed for MMW.
20,000 Days on Earth which premiered at Sundance to much acclaim. A documentary-not-documentary about the life and times of Australia's dark poet laureate, Nick Cave, it integrates archive and concert footage with re-enactment and staged scenes that may not represent the truth, as it exactly happened, but does represent the truth as it's lived and remembered.
Set over a single day, and directed by visual artists Iain Forsyth and Jane Pollard, it is a smouldering, evocative dive into Cave's myth and his thoughtful, self-aware reflections on the creative process. It is not surprising that Cave has chosen such an innovative way to explore his legacy considering his history with and in some amazing films - from playing a deranged prisoner in Ghosts of the Civil Dead to writing The Proposition, both directed by John Hillcoat.
Track 24 hours with Cave, and a few with Kylie Minogue, that didn't necessarily happen but, nonetheless, elevate the music documentary into warped biopic territory. Then go home and put The Birthday Party on the stereo.

item.title: The Kelvin Club Presents
item.description:
The organisers behind St. Jerome's Laneway Festival deliver their first official Melbourne Music Week event at The Kelvin Club.
This showcase features some of Melbourne's top emerging artists including Japanese Wallpaper, LUCIANBLOMKAMP and Klo.
Staying true to Laneway's objective of hosting forward-thinking artists in unique locations, the historic inner-city venue The Kelvin Club makes for the perfect match.

item.title: The Toff in Town Presents
item.description:
Big local sounds - bellowing vocals and gaining pop by frantic bleeps and turns - take over The Toff in Town for Live Music Safari.
Electronic RnB/soul group The Harpoons are renowned for packing dancefloors, while hyperactive beat-makers Parking Lot Experiments elevate with a whirlwind of hedonistic fun and mayhem.

item.title: Cherry Bar Presents
item.description:
Melbourne's iconic Cherry Bar is religiously rock and roll, but their Soul Thursdays remain one of Melbourne's longest running soul/funk residencies. For Live Music Safari, Cherry Bar shines the spotlight on three emerging local acts from the vibrant soul scene - The Harlots, Stella Angelico and Kingston Crown.
Bluesy rock outfit and triple j Unearthed actThe Harlots have been playing sell-out shows since launching their acclaimed double EP, Coarse Tunes - Parts 1 and 2, and following this year's release, 'Somewhere To Go'.
Stella Angelico have described their style as akin to a soul/rock-meets-disco/Bond soundtrack. Expect big vocals and some serious bass swing to get the dancefloor pumping.
Kingston Crown, a band born from of a shared love of soul and RnB and another triple j Unearthed success story, finish the night's fiery line-up.

item.title: Magic Mountain Band + Ben Byrne
item.description:
Welcome to The Institute Presents... Lost Empire - a series of wonderful one-off gigs in unique and special spaces curated exclusively for MMW. The series combines our city's magnificent music culture with its inventive spirit by showcasing great artists in rare locations that would normally be off limits.
Enter the depths of a functioning electrical substation - including its original 1959 control room - to witness the wonder of Magic Mountain Band in full flight alongside Ben Byrne's enigmatic genius.
Numbers are limited and RSVP is essential. While entry is free, after the show, organisers invite audiences to pay what they think the show was worth and proceeds go to the artists.
Lost Empire offers a chance to break down the typical band-stage-crowd dynamic in favour of genuine exchange. All shows are designed in a way that is fundamentally sustainable - small-scale, local and low impact.
Scour the program for four other Lost Empire shows.

item.title: Bennetts Lane Jazz Club presents
item.description:
Bennetts Lane Jazz Club present two rooms of exhilarating live jazz for Live Music Safari.
Swing is the Thing, featuring music from Kelsey James and The Furbelows and dance by Studio 1929, celebrates rollicking 1920s and 30s swing, jive and Lindy Hop. Enter this room and be immersed in the heyday of toe-tapping jazz via the Mills Brothers, Andrews Sisters and Boswell Sisters.
On their resident stage, the Bennetts Lane Big Band astound with the vitality of their contemporary, original big band sounds. Drawing from the very best and innovative talent in Melbourne today, the band features Joseph O'Connor, James Macaulay, Tom Noonan, Kieran Hensey, Jason McMahon, Jon Hunt, Ben Harrison, Callum G'Froerer, Nick Pietsch, Matt McGeachin, Marty Holoubek and James McLean.
Delight in this wonderful spectacle of jazz music and dance, and spend an evening discovering this exuberant and revolutionary art form.

item.title: Hunt. Tram. Party.
item.description:
Tram Sessions are booting off commuters and taking over Melbourne's favourite mode of transport for the ultimate moving music party - Hunt. Tram. Party.
The night begins with a treasure hunt of sorts around Melbourne's CBD, with clues located by buskers, record stores and live music venues. Music lovers converge as X marks the spot on board an exclusive tram party. Rattle and groove across the city with a surprise, up-close-and-personal performance from a secret artist.
The final stop is Ding Dong Lounge where the doors open for Live Music Safari and the stage lights up with local band, Jakubi.
Jump on and jam on for this one of a kind Melbourne experience.

item.title: Live Music Safari launch: Kingswood
item.description:
Indie rock band Kingswood launch this year's Live Music Safari with a special performance at the flagship venue of Melbourne Music Week, Queen Victoria Market.
Kingswood's debut album, produced by Vance Powell (Jack White, Arctic Monkeys and Kings of Leon) in Nashville USA, was released earlier this year and stormed straight to number 6 on the ARIA charts.
Kingswood members are also avid motorbike lovers. In this spirit, Harley-Davidson Street 500 have built The Shed, a temporary motorbike inspired hangout and celebration of creative culture, at Queen Victoria Market for Melbourne Music Week.
Fans can get their hands on the limited number of tickets available for this exclusive opening party through various competitions and promotions in the weeks leading up to the event.

item.title: FasterLouder Lunchbox Series
item.description:
Let music break the daily grind with a full bill of free lunchtime gigs as part of this year's FasterLouder Lunchbox Series at the new flagship venue of MMW, QVM. Since 2010, this popular series has been enlivening the city and providing a welcome interruption to work days. At Lunchbox gigs, enjoy some of the tastiest produce QVM has to offer while a stable of Australian talent take to the stage.
Sui et Sui - Monday 17 November, 12.30pm Sui Zhen, the alias of Becky Sui Zhen, performs her own version of Japanese post punk through a dreamy Balearic-bossa nova filter with her live band Sui et Sui.
Amaya Laucirica - Tuesday 18 November, 12.30pm Laucirica captivates with her beautiful folk melodies and heavenly vocals at one of her final performances before she relocates to Berlin in 2015.
Gold Class - Wednesday 19 November, 12.30pm See Melbourne rock outfit Gold Class bring their fresh savagery and contemporary working-class politics to bright rhythms that hark back to the post punk eras of 1980s Australia and England.
Holy Lotus - Thursday 20 November, 12.30pm Spend lunchtime with Holy Lotus as they perform the kind of joyful, sunny synth pop that suggests they have the power to put winter on hold.
Peter Bibby - Friday 21 November, 12.30pm Make a Friday lunch date with larrikin Peter Bibby whose cigarette-laced vocals and folk/bluesy guitar are deeply embedded in the Australian idiom.

item.title: Tangerine Dream play Sorcerer
item.description:
Founded in 1967, Tangerine Dream may have undergone many line-up changes but their distinctive and immersive sound remains incredibly potent and enormously influential. The score to William Friedkin's epic jungle thriller Sorcerer rates as one of the band's most successful musical releases and is very much a concept album independent of the film.
For the first time in Australia, this legendary German outfit play the complete score to Sorcerer. Presented in association with the film festival CPH PIX and direct from sellout houses in Copenhagen, the film acts as a haunting backdrop to this special live show.
In trademark Tangerine Dream style, layer upon layer of deep synth and soaring electronic peaks are set against Friedkin's exciting and gripping images to provide a truly unforgettable experience.
The film itself has its roots in Henri-Georges Clouzot's classic 1953 psychological thriller The Wages of Fear, where a group of mercenaries are charged with transporting trucks of nitro-glycerine through the South American jungle. But Tangerine Dream's touch rips the story out of the 1950s and places it firmly in the 1970s with a good dash of thumping rhythm laced with heavy psychedelia.
Hear the score in full and uninterrupted for this one-off, truly memorable event.
Please note - the film screens as a visual backdrop to Tangerine Dream's live performance.

item.title: Massive Hip-Hop Choir for Babies
item.description:
Join the Massive Hip-Hop Choir for this workshop designed specifically for babes in arms and crawlers with their carer.
Experience the joy of being together at the centre of this mass singing event, as vocalist and musician Andrea Khoza is joined by young emerging artists from Massive to perform in the round.
Uplifting and accessible, the workshop repertoire combines body percussion and choral singing with rhythmic poetry. The artist team teach simple refrains and rhythms to parents and babies to accompany Massive tracks. Musical styles include gospel, rhythm and blues, and world music.
All children must be accompanied by an adult and it is recommended that parents bring a baby pack or carrier to ensure their hands are free.

item.title: The Telepathy Project + Sophia Brous
item.description:
Delve into the unconscious spaces of Melbourne's shared gardens, architecture and imagination with this mind-wandering sonic experience.
As part of MPavilion's One Night Stand series of interventions, The Telepathy Project (Veronica Kent and Sean Peoples) invite special guests including hypnotic chanteuse Sophia Brous, following on from her participation in The Barbican Centre's In Dreams: David Lynch Revisited, to come together and celebrate all things celestial for this series of nocturnal and dawn adventures
The resultant recordings of the night's adventures will become a free, sonic experience throughout the week in MPavilion.
This project has been funded as part of the VCA and MCM New Initiatives program, supported by the State Government through Arts Victoria.

item.title: Section 8 and Ferdydurke present
item.description:
Section 8 and Ferdydurke are building a solid reputation for luring crowds with a new era of laneway parties. The two venues pool their highly-tuned party sensibilities to present ZOO, a sensory overload and audio-visual extravaganza for Live Music Safari in Tattersalls Lane.
The iconic laneway closes for a barrage of performance - banging drums, clashing guitars and masterful beats; performance art; improvised approaches to staging and lighting; and a giant, four-storey-high projection wall.
The Zoo line-up includes Brawther, City Calm Down and Paces.

item.title: The Hi-Fi presents
item.description:
The Hi-Fi is proud to present A Basement Show, a nod to the up-and-comers - Magic America, The Good Morrows, Bad Family, Where's Joss and more.
Magic America are the psych rock quartet generating hype and following after the recent release of their single 'I thought I told you'. In the words of Tone Deaf, 'Magic America blend Brit-pop hooks with psyched out rock n roll vibes; they are the local band for fans of The Dandy Warhols, Oasis, and Primal Scream.'
Get set for a wild live set from the Melbourne power-pop-rock outfit The Good Morrows who are duly enjoying praise on the back of their recent single 'Running Around'.
Melbourne's Bad Family are back at The Hi Fi after a phenomenal last minute show in 2013 and Where's Joss, who have spent the year gigging and supporting large shows, complete the stellar line-up.
Toast some of Melbourne's great emerging bands at this energetic Live Music Safari event.

item.title: The Liberty Social presents
item.description:
Requiem present an evening of gothic subcultures at Melbourne dive bar, The Liberty Social.
The city's own bat cave will see Adelaide's Rule of Thirds play songs from their highly-anticipated, long-play debut - a soundtrack to our sparse and mysterious red country. This sextet's wailing female vocals over lashings of guitar, reverberant synth and militant bass and drums is a fresh take on 1970s and 80s Australian gothic rock.
Supports include local purveyors of wave in Repairs, Lakes with their pummelling tribal-rhythms and young upstarts Habits, while trad-goth DJs and members of NUN program sound all evening.
Throughout the night contemporary dance performance artist Agent Cleave leads a troupe of gothicka.
Be swept up in death rock, industrial, gothic and dark wave.

item.title: The Roller Jam
item.description:
Four-man collective Foreign Brothers are back to transform 1000 £ Bend into a roller disco of cosmic proportions. Over the course of three nights, the space hosts a line-up of Melbourne's best DJ crews and live bands to keep the party rolling.
Super sleek, trip-hop duo ALTA headline the Friday night edition with support from Hans DC, Nam, JPS, Edd Fisher and Sean Deans.
Saturday night heralds the Strictly Vinyl party with purveyors of high-class dance music - Jimmy James and DJ Jnett - headlining alongside a very special guest who is yet to be announced.
In keeping with the philosophy of past Foreign Brothers events, The Roller Jam is intended to bring together people of diverse backgrounds under the banner of peace, love, unity and fun.
Skates are available for hire; fluoro lycra, sweat band sets and glitter are optional. Get ready to roll.

item.title: 1000 £ Bend Presents
item.description:
Roll on in to Live Music Safari as Foreign Brothers transform 1000 £ Bend into a roller disco of cosmic proportions and Northside Records present a full line-up of their signature sounds, from hip-hop to soul and reggae through to funk.
Mondo Freaks, the 1980s funk/post-disco crew, bring their layers of synth and extended breaks to the rink and Triple R presenter Chris Gill plugs local winners to keep people rolling with steeze.
PBS's DJ Manchild plays his colourful mix of Bollywood funk, fiery Columbian-salsa and hip-hop and stepping up the calypso, fellow locals Ms Butt and Lewis Cancut serve up their blend of world beats, percussive house and tropical disco.
Holding the philosophy of past Foreign Brothers events, The Roller Jam is intended to bring together people of diverse backgrounds under the banner of peace, love, unity and fun.
Skates are available for hire; fluoro lycra, sweat band sets and glitter are optional. Get ready to roll.

item.title: Soul Safari + The Perfections + Mayfield
item.description:
Embark on an intimate and rousing, genre-spanning journey as Melbourne's best soul bands warm the city for this special edition of Fed Square Live, the weekly summer music series hosted by Fed Square.
Melbourne's Soul Safari have been making waves across Australia. These groove-based music makers wow crowds with their passionate and energetic performances and leave audiences begging for an encore. Blending neo soul, funk, RnB and hip-hop, this is a band with a story to tell.
Next up are The Perfections and their mix of dirty and sweet garage soul. Describing themselves as 'the lovechild of Otis Redding and The Stooges', lead singer Christina sets the stage alight with her commanding vocals and glitter-tastic antics.
The trio of soulful performances rounds out with Mayfield, a vibrant and solid five piece funk/soul crew, playing deep, rich originals. With a raw and honest sound that manages to be fun and electrifying at the same time, Mayfield are guaranteed to get punters up and dancing.

item.title: Lounge Presents
item.description:
Lounge, one of Melbourne's much-loved music venues, joins the dots between emerging and established artists to showcase our city's highly-revered electronic music labels on two stages and with a laneway party for Live Music Safari.
Sleep D comprises Corey Kikos and Maryos Syawish. Part of the delectable Butter Sessions fleet, this artistic duo have spent the best part of their youth exploring sonic soundscapes and ways to share them with other people.
Harvey Sutherland creates warm floating textures of bass and noodling keys with nods to early techno and the 909 drum machine. He is joined by PhD student Tom Day, who first started making music as a means to escape. Day creates lush, cinematic, piano-based pieces layered with electronic hooks.
Cale Sexton, a hardcore punk kid from way back, is up next. Sexton's switch to electronic music happened recently, but in just a short time he has managed to turn heads and hearts on dancefloors.
Fellow champions of the techno scene, Jake Blood, Kangaroo Skull, Voitek and PWD join the fold and M5K brings the beats for this hometown throwdown.

item.title: Live Music Safari Kitchens
item.description:
For Live Music Safari, fourteen of Melbourne's much-loved and iconic live music venues open their doors for a wild night of free gigs and parties, and, for the first time, some are offering food as well.
Try the black angus, kangaroo or saganaki burgers or a spicy quesadilla at 1000 £ Bend. Full menu
Snack on Boney's jalapeno donuts, chicken kofta or cashew and carrot bao buns or fill a bigger appetite with the beef brisket. Full menu
Gloria Swanston's Kitchen at Lounge makes mouth-watering American classics like philly-cheese steaks, Texan BBQ ribs and southern fried green tomato sliders. Full menu
Treat yourself to Thai flavours - perhaps a betel leaf salad with salmon or mushroom dumpling green curry - courtesy of Choo Choo's at The Toff in Town. Full menu
Girl with the Gris Gris serve home-style, Louisiana cooking with a Creole and Cajun menu at Ding Dong. MMW ticket holders can take advantage of their special Live Music Safari offer - an Abita beer and chicken and sausage gumbo for $15. Full menu
Ferdydurke top star-studded frankfurters like the Fred Savage (frank with tequila infused chunky salsa, jalapenos, cheese and sour cream) and nachos too. Full menu
Huxtaburger now have a pop-up kitchen at The John Curtin Hotel. From the Denise to the Sondra, select any one of their much-loved burgers. Full menu
The Kelvin Club plates up carbonara croquets, burgers and an extensive list of cheesy toasties. Full menu
Fancy Hank's BBQ Joint serves traditional American-style, slow-cooked BBQ at The Mercat. Full menu
Miss Katies Crab Shack at The Public Bar boasts a low country boil, fried chicken, burgers and more made using produce from QVM. Full menu

item.title: Boney presents
item.description:
Boney have assembled a slew of Melbourne's chief electronic acts for a Live Music Safari party that spans over two levels, spills into Magic Mountain next door and flows out to a laneway party in Westwood Place.
Upstairs at Boney, Nic Hamilton and This Thing artists Dylan Michél, Kane Ikin and Coup D'etat examine the synchronicity between the contemporary creation of music and video as sounds and visuals are manufactured, found, re-filmed, blurred, slowed-down, sped-up, spliced and reconstructed.
Microwave synth star Versaj (aka Kirkis) plays heartfelt boogie jams to Silentjay and Julien Love serenades with Latin tracks in the downstairs area.
At Magic Mountain, disco darlings Misty Nights facilitate the quest to euphoric, psychedelic disco mayhem. Fashioned by the dream team Danny Hotep and Simon Barrel, Misty Nights steer the most discerning dancefloor in Melbourne.
In the laneway, Edd Fisher and Simon TK of Wax'o Paradiso play with guest Jimmy Caution and support comes from dance crew The Fandroids. Sample the fruits of the concrete jungle as these artists conjure the depths of the Amazon with their impeccable taste in tropical rhythms for Live Music Safari.

item.title: Thomas Jeppe + Safia
item.description:
Residency combines visual art, live music and a knockout drinks menu.
Open for three nights, only for MMW, this warehouse pop-up bar transforms with the work of artist-in-residence, the acclaimed Australian visual artist, Thomas Jeppe.
But Residency is not a traditional art gallery exhibition or party; in fact, none of the art is for sale. Instead, Jeppe receives 50% of the profits from the bar - a revolutionary way to support a local artist and simultaneously enjoy good music.
On the Saturday night, witness the return of indie-electro wunderkinds SAFIA to the Melbourne stage and enjoy music from a killer queue of local DJ talent.

item.title: Requiem For Dalinka
item.description:
The Artisan Collective proudly present the premiere season of Requiem For Dalinka, a story by Peter Marks at Gasworks Arts Park.
Who will survive when the final curtain falls? May 1945, Far East Poland. Rumour has is that the war is coming to an end.
Concentration camp Dalinka holds only four surviving prisoners; a quartet of Klezmer musicians who have been spared so that they might provide entertainment for the SS soldiers. Desperate to stay alive, they plot to overthrow the Nazis. Will the allies arrive in time? Or will the "Final Solution" be implemented before there's any chance of escape?
Requiem for Dalinka combines exquisite Klezmer, classical and a cappella song with a story that will keep audiences guessing at every turn. This new Australian work explores the perseverance and fragility of the human spirit, music as food for the soul, and the boundaries of allegiance in some of the most extreme circumstances.

item.title: Morning Ritual
item.description:
A call for music lovers to rise and shine, Morning Ritual's free morning gigs are back to plant big smiles on faces, first-thing.
Now an Melbourne Music Week breakfast staple, Morning Ritual offers a superior start to the day. Expect a mixture of genres to complement the early(ish) rise. This year's all-local line-up is as feel good as bircher and has the heart of a BLT, all happily perked-up with two shots of espresso.
The birds have been beating people to it since the dawn of time; this is a chance to get ahead and catch the worm (metaphorically, not digestively). The line-up is well-worth the morning effort.

item.title: Synesthesia
item.description:
As part of their debut partnership with Melbourne Music Week, Clear Design, a brand design and brand strategy studio based in Fitzroy, coordinates and curates a poster exhibition to be featured at this year's flagship venue, Queen Victoria Market.
Contributing artists have been asked to visualise and interpret their association with Melbourne and music through a variety of creative mediums including photography, art, design, illustration and words. The resultant creations make up the exhibition which is on display throughout Melbourne Music Week 2014.

item.title: Garden of Forking Paths
item.description:
Ever wanted to touch the artwork? Now you can. Play an original 1980s computer game, the world's first ever art game, on a historic Commodore 64 machine!
Get your hands on a CD-rom! See what the internet used to look like when it first began. Talk to a robot on a vintage TV! See how iPads are your own personal mini art gallery. Play with the latest in technology: the cutting edge Oculus Rift headwear!
dLux MediaArts presents Garden of Forking Paths, a daring exhibition curated by Neil Jenkins which draws together notable historic and contemporary examples of computer games that push the bounds of the genre and break the orthodox set of rules and redefine what a game, or an artwork, can be.

item.title: Grasslands
item.description:
Grasslands is a living installation that gathers over 10,000 indigenous plants. This organic composition aims to recreate the vast grass plains that stretched over the State Library of Victoria site before it was established in the mid-nineteenth century.
Linda Tegg conceived of this site-specific project during her 2012 Georges Mora Foundation Fellowship at the State Library of Victoria. Researching the original flora of this site, the artist found that most available data was interpretative, from Victorian landscape paintings to illustrated maps.
Looking to expand her sources of knowledge, Tegg collaborated with horticulturist John Delpratt and the University of Melbourne to source, grow and nurture the 10,000 indigenous plants and grasses that make up Grasslands.
The result is a transformation of history and nature by artistic imagination, inviting us to visualise the layers of memory and place.
This project has been assisted by the Australian Government through the Australia Council, its arts funding and advisory body and the Victorian Government through Arts Victoria. Grasslands has also been supported by the City of Melbourne through the Arts Grant Program.
This project is supported by University of Melbourne - Burnley Campus, Department of Resource Management and Geography. Grasslands is the result of a Georges Mora Foundation Fellowship at the State Library of Victoria.
Source: City of Melbourne What's On

item.title: Bruno Leti – Landscapes of the Soul
item.description:
The Museo Italiano hosts an exhibition of Bruno Leti's work revisiting some fifty years of art-making.
Leti is represented in major Australian national, state and regional galleries and in public and private collections internationally. His art has also been the object of several monographs by leading art historians. Since his emigration from Italy in 1952, Bruno's Italianness has grown as an essential component of his artistic inspiration, nurtured by his childhood memories, by his studies in art history, by his frequent journeys to his native country and by an ongoing engagement with Italian art and literature.
Leti has travelled and worked widely in Europe, America and Asia, drawing inspiration from very diverse natural and cultural landscapes. Bruno describes himself as an Australian artist and indeed the multiculturalism and cosmopolitanism to which Bruno has made a signal contribution in the world of art, are by now quintessentially Australian traits.
The exhibition will be launched by Sir James Gobbo, and guest speaker Professor Sasha Grishin (Australian National University) will introduce the exhibition.

item.title: British Heraldry of the Great War
item.description:
This lecture, largely illustrated with images from the records of the College of Arms, will discuss the representation of the Great War in the armorial bearings granted to various military and naval commanders, armament manufacturers and others. The arms will be set in the context of older English heraldic traditions. The heraldic consequences of George V's desire to sever his family's ties with Germany will also be discussed.
The lecture will be presented by David Vines White and be held in the Auditorium, Education Centre at the Shrine of Remembrance
The event is free but gold coin donation welcome.

British Heraldry of the Great War

item.title: Framed Movements
item.description:
Presented by Melbourne Festival and Australian Centre for Contemporary Art, Framed Movements investigates the potential that lies at the shifting boundaries between dance and art.
Exploring the many ways a movement based approach to the occupation of time and space is practised not only in dance but increasingly in the realm of contemporary art, the exhibition brings together a series of Australian and international artists who use a choreographic approach in their work.
A series of performances will accompany the exhibition, drawing attention to the potential of the body in space and its ability to draw you into a physical conversation with the world around you.
Exhibiting artists: Gwenneth Boelens, Ann Carlson & Mary Ellen Strom, Lane Cormick, Brian Fuata, Alicia Frankovich, Agatha Gothe-Snape, Nathan Gray, Helen Grogan, Maria Hassabi, Joachim Koester, Paulina Olowska, Jess Olivieri, Hayley Forward & Parachutes for Ladies, Emily Roysdon, Sandra Selig and Lee Serle.

item.title: EIKON: Icons of the Orthodox Christian World
item.description:
The rich tradition of Eastern Christian spirituality and imagery will be celebrated with the special exhibition EIKON: Icons of the Orthodox Christian World.
Discover the extraordinary power of icons, which have sustained and shaped belief in different times and contexts, sometimes against significant odds. Icons are beautiful sacred portraits, glowing with rich colours and gold leaf, but for Orthodox Christians they also represent the Divine Presence - they have been referred to as 'windows on Heaven'.
EIKON brings eighty high quality works, including some really sumptuous examples of Orthodox art. Most of the icons in the show originate from Greece and Russia, with examples as well from Cyprus, Syria and Palestine, and range in time from the twelfth to the beginning of the nineteenth centuries.
Viewing the exhibition will be a special event, with dramatic lighting and a soundscape incorporating traditional chanting, bells and other sounds of an Orthodox service, recreating the original setting of the works.
The exhibition draws mainly from the magnificent private collection of former Australian diplomat John McCarthy, with additional loans from the National Gallery of Victoria, from the Abbey Museum of Art and Archaeology in Queensland and from Sir Richard Temple Bt, whose Temple Gallery in London is a leading centre for the study, restoration and exhibition of ancient icons and sacred art.
EIKON will be accompanied by a lavishly illustrated catalogue, as well as specially produced Christmas cards and other souvenirs. There will also be a schedule of education and public programs, including concerts of Greek and Russian-inspired music.
Join one of the Gallery's dedicated Guides on a special tour through the exhibition to hear some of the stories behind the artworks. Tours will run daily at 11.30am from Wednesdays to Sundays during the run of the exhibition.

image.altText: EIKON: Icons of the Orthodox Christian World

item.title: Imhoff: a life of grain & pixels
item.description:
An exhibition at the Art Gallery of Ballarat highlights the work of Robert Imhoff, an Australian photographer and filmmaker who not only built up a very successful career as a commercial photographer but also established a reputation as one of Australia's leading portrait photographers.
Imhoff's love affair with photography began in the same way as it did for many young photographers: with a Kodak Box Brownie, while his professional career started after studying photography at RMIT in the late 1960s.
A career break came when he was invited to do a four-page spread featuring Wittner Shoes for insertion in the March 1971 edition of Vogue Australia. The images featured shoes on model's feet that were draped around a naked female body. Although the shot featuring Gaye Baker doesn't show much flesh by today's standards, the use of the naked female form was seen as ground-breaking for Vogue Australia.
Imhoff tended to work for the upper end of the consumer market, undertaking commissions for perfume, cars, fashion and airlines.
This retrospective exhibition, Imhoff: A life of grains and pixels, documents his career as a professional photographer and filmmaker, including portraits of celebrities and the not so well known, photography for specialist food magazines that began to emerge in the 1970s, and assignments for a number of multinational companies.

image.altText: Imhoff: a life of grain & pixels

item.title: Santa's Magical Kingdom
item.description:
Santa's Magical Kingdom, in collaboration with Santa Claus's North Pole Corporation, have signed an exclusive deal to once again bring all the magic of Christmas to Melbourne in 2014!
After an astoundingly successful event in 2013, which was visited by people from all around Australia, Santa's Magical Kingdom will return in 2014 bigger and better than ever at a new home, Caulfield Racecourse.
Santa's Magical Kingdom brings all the wonder and joy of a traditional Christmas. This interactive walk-through is an enchanting experience that includes everything that you love about Christmas. Get ready to be amazed as you see the magic of Christmas come to life!
Open to the public from 15 November to 23 December, Santa's Magical Kingdom will deliver a Christmas wonderland full of activities that will capture the imagination of children & parents everywhere.
The event will include:
- A magical Christmas walk-through wonderland - Snowland with the all new Snow Castle - A free gift, when you meet Santa - A brand new International Christmas Circus Spectacular - Roving Christmas characters - Gingerbread Land, where you can decorate your own gingerbread man - Interactive storytelling with Mrs Claus - Amusement Rides & Games, including laughing clowns, a Carousel, Santa's Sleigh Ride, the Giant Ferris Wheel and Australia's Largest Super Slide! - Plus so much more fun for the whole family

item.title: Gawang II - Aboriginal Portrait Exhibition
item.description:
In conjunction with the Archibald Prize exhibition at the Mornington Peninsula Regional Gallery, Baluk Arts presents Gawang II - an exhibition of Aboriginal Portraits by Aboriginal People.
Featuring Award winning artists Ray Thomas, Lisa Waup, Bea Edwards and many more, Gawang II is a great way to learn about many different Aboriginal people, their lives and character.

item.title: The Alcove Art Shop Christmas A'Fair Exhibition
item.description:
The annual Alcove Art Shop Christmas A'fair will bring together a wonderful array of beautifully hand-crafted items by their artisans. The artists create unique works including ceramics, jewellery, paintings, woodwork, cards and textiles, just to name a few.
They invite you to join them during this exhibition and delight in the creations. You may even find something special to take home, for yourself or your loved ones.
